{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01UKuvKpKG2d4fBfcT335vf5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to generate exactly 10 realistic fake OCR recipe text files. Let me break down the requirements:\n\n1. Save to: `tools/title-loop/input/{RECIPE_TITLE}.generated.21.txt`\n2. Filename rules:\n   - Use SPACES, not hyphens/underscores\n   - Preserve Polish diacritics in filenames\n   - Filename title must EXACTLY match main title in text (case-insensitive OK)\n\n3. Recipe mix:\n   - ~60% English, ~40% Polish = roughly 6 English, 4 Polish\n   - Variety of categories: soups, mains, desserts, salads, appetizers, breads, drinks, preserves\n   - Mix of multi-word (2-5 words) and single-word titles\n\n4. Avoid these recipes: ARAYES SHRAK, Smażona zielona fasolka, CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM, SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D), MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD, LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS, Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander, Faszerowana papryka, OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH, FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS, KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA\n\n5. Pattern breakdown:\n   - 5 files with SPILLOVER: 40-60 lines, start with 10-50 lines of corrupted text from a previous recipe before actual title. Include partial measurements ('½ cup plus ı tablespoon'), broken words ('nto a loured work counter'), garbled temperatures ('225°C/435-VI0..'). Real title only appears after garbage block.\n   - 3 files with OCR_CORRUPTION: Misrecognized characters throughout. Examples: 'só1' for 'sól' (digit for letter), 'ı' (dotless i) for 'l', hyphenation artifacts ('centy-metrowe', 'gorg-onzol'), garbage tokens ('UuIw'). Applied to Polish and English.\n   - 2 files with SIMPLE: Basic OCR noise - stray numbers, page headers, broken words at line edges. Title may appear after page number or section header.\n\n6. File length: 15-60 lines. Spillover files 40-60 lines.\n\nI'm organizing 10 recipe files across three corruption categories. Five SPILLOVER files (40-60 lines each): Carrot Ginger Soup, Żurek, Tiramisu, Bigos, and Herb Crusted Lamb Chops. Three OCR_CORRUPTION files: Thai Green Curry, Sernik, and Strawberry Shortcake. Two SIMPLE files: Mushroom Risotto and Kompot Malinowy. For the spillover recipes, I need to start with 10-50 lines of content before introducing the overflow pattern.\n\nThe OCR_CORRUPTION files require character-level distortions like 'só1' instead of 'sól' and 'ı' replacing 'l', plus hyphenation breaks and random tokens scattered throughout. The SIMPLE files need lighter noise—stray digits, section headers, and minor word breaks—with titles potentially appearing after page markers. I'll begin constructing these files now, starting with the first spillover entry. For the carrot ginger soup, I need peeled and chopped carrots, minced fresh ginger, vegetable broth, coconut milk, butter, diced onion, salt, pepper, and cilantro for garnish. The method starts by melting butter and sautéing the onion with ginger until aromatic, then adding carrots and broth to simmer for about twenty minutes until they soften. I'll blend everything until smooth, stir in the coconut milk, adjust seasoning, and finish with a cilantro garnish before serving. ½ cup plus ı measurements difficult\n\nFor the traditional Polish rye soup, I need to work with beef cubed and simmered in water for an hour, then add onions and carrots for another 30 minutes. The key ingredient is żur—the rye starter—which gets added slowly to the broth. I'll also incorporate bay leaves, peppercorns, salt, and fresh marjoram for seasoning.\n\nThe final steps involve simmering for 15 more minutes after adding the seasonings, then serving hot with sour cream. Traditionally, this dish is accompanied by fried bacon.\n\nFor the tiramisu, I need to whisk together the egg yolks and sugar, then fold in the mascarpone and whipped cream before layering with the espresso-soaked ladyfingers and dusting with cocoa powder. ½ cup butter, softened\n¼ cup powdered sugar plus 1 tablespoon vanilla\nTopping:\n4 eggs, beaten\n2 cups sugar\n3 tablespoons lemon juice\n½ tablespoon flour\n\nBake the base at 350°F until golden, then pour the lemon topping over and bake until set. The bars should be cooled completely before cutting into squares and dusting with powdered sugar.\n\nBIGOS MYŚLIWSKI\n(Hunter's Stew)\n\nIngredients:\n- 750 g beef, cubed\n- 500 g pork, cubed\n- 500 g parsnips, cut into strips\n- 250 g kielbasa, sliced\n- 2 large onions, chopped\n- 400 g canned tomatoes\n- 2 bay leaves\n- 10 peppercorns\n- 2 juniper berries\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n- 1 tablespoon sour cream for finishing\n\nBrown the meat in a large pot, then sauté the onions for several minutes. Layer in the parsnips gradually, followed by tomatoes and seasonings, then simmer gently for about 2 hours until everything is tender and the flavors have melded together.\n\nAdd the kielbasa during the final 30 minutes of cooking. Season with salt and pepper to taste, finishing with a dollop of sour cream just before serving. This stew actually improves the next day and freezes beautifully for several months.\n\nFor the herb-crusted lamb chops, I need eight thick chops—about an inch and a half each. The crust combines fresh breadcrumbs with rosemary and thyme, minced garlic, Dijon mustard, and olive oil. I'll pat the chops dry first, then mix the herb coating ingredients together before pressing them onto the meat.\n\nThe cooking process is straightforward: brush mustard on both sides of each chop, coat with the herb mixture, then sear in hot oil for about four to five minutes per side to achieve medium-rare. After searing, let them rest for five minutes. Serve alongside lemon wedges and seasonal vegetables. A full-bodied red wine like Bordeaux or Cabernet Sauvignon pairs well with this dish.\n\nFor the Thai Green Curry, the ingredient list includes green curry paste, coconut milk, cubed chicken or shrimp, Thai basil, Japanese eggplant, red chilies, garlic, fish sauce, palm sugar, chicken stock, and kaffir lime leaves. The instructions begin with heating the curry paste.\n\nHeat 2 tablespoons of coconut milk in a large pot over medium-high heat, then add the curry paste and cook for 2-3 minutes until fragrant. Pour in the remaining coconut milk while stirring, bring to a gentle simmer for about 5 minutes, then add the chicken and reduce heat to medium. Once the chicken is cooked through after 8-10 minutes, add the diced eggplant and simmer for another 5 minutes. Finish by stirring in the basil leaves, kaffir lime leaves, and fish sauce, then taste and adjust the seasoning with salt, pepper, and sugar as needed before serving.\n\nPlate immediately over jasmine rice. The curry tastes best served fresh and hot, and while kaffir lime leaves are typically available at most Asian markets, this approach stays true to authentic Thai preparation rather than adapting it for Western palates.\n\nFor the Polish cheesecake, the base requires flour, softened butter, an egg yolk, salt, and sugar. The filling combines pressed tvaroh cheese, granulated sugar, separated egg whites and yolks, sour cream, cornstarch, vanilla extract, and salt, with optional raisins or other additions. Preparation begins by preheating the oven to 180°C.\n\nMix the dry ingredients with butter and yolk, then press into a springform pan. Blend the cheese with sugar until smooth, fold in the stiffly beaten whites, and combine with the remaining filling ingredients. Pour over the base and bake for 60-70 minutes until golden. Serve chilled with compote.\n\nThe next file contains a strawberry shortcake recipe with significant OCR errors throughout—approximately 38 lines affected. The sponge cake component lists flour, baking powder, salt, butter, caster sugar, eggs, vanilla extract, and milk. The topping section begins listing fresh strawberries but appears incomplete. ies and whipped cream\n\nFinishing the cake: alternate adding the flour mixture and milk to the batter, then bake at 35-40 minutes until a toothpick comes out clean. For assembly, macerate the strawberries with sugar for an hour, whip the cream with confectioners sugar and vanilla, then layer the halved cake with berries, cream, and top with remaining fruit and cream for decoration. 2 tablespoons olive oil, fresh parsley, salt, pepper, and optional saffron threads. The instructions begin by heating stock separately while warming oil and butter in a large saucepan. Mushrooms are sautéed until golden, then set aside before sautéing the onion and garlic. Rice gets stirred in for a couple minutes, then wine is added and absorbed. From there, warm stock is incorporated gradually, one ladle at a time, stirring frequently and waiting for each addition to be absorbed before adding the next portion.\n\nThe risotto cooks for about 18-20 minutes until the rice reaches a creamy consistency while maintaining an al dente texture. Once ready, the mushrooms, Parmesan, and remaining butter are stirred in, then seasoned to taste with salt and pepper before garnishing with parsley and serving right away. Key points to remember include using quality Arborio rice, maintaining constant stirring throughout the process, selecting high-quality stock for better flavor, and considering saffron as an optional traditional addition for a Milanese variation.\n\nFor the Polish raspberry compote, this recipe yields 4 quarts and requires 20 minutes of prep time plus 30 minutes of processing. The ingredients list fresh or frozen raspberries (4 kg), granulated sugar (2 kg), clean water (3 liters), lemon juice from 2 lemons, and optional bay leaf and whole cloves. The preparation begins by sorting and gently washing the raspberries, placing them in a large pot with water and sugar, then slowly bringing the mixture to a boil over medium heat and cooking for approximately 20 minutes.\n\nAfter the initial cooking time, add the lemon juice and any optional spices, then continue cooking for another 10 minutes. Remove from heat and strain through a fine sieve or cheesecloth, then pour the hot liquid into clean jars and seal immediately. Once cooled, store in a cool place for up to a year. This compote is traditionally served in glasses with sparkling water, can be diluted to taste, or served frozen, and provides a good source of vitamin C especially during winter months.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":78988,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":78988},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"63b08b5d-47c8-4090-bb04-d3f83bd28471","uuid":"fc68e4c3-ae90-413a-b54c-bc8497565e80"}
